{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_014u99XAstsde8yRRtwZGmgd","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<project xmlns=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0\"\n     2→         xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"\n     3→         xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd\">\n     4→  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>\n     5→  \n     6→  <parent>\n     7→    <groupId>jakarta.tutorial</groupId>\n     8→    <artifactId>roster</artifactId>\n     9→    <version>1.0.0</version>\n    10→  </parent>\n    11→  \n    12→  <artifactId>roster-ear</artifactId>\n    13→  <packaging>ear</packaging>\n    14→\n    15→  <properties>\n    16→    <maven.compiler.source>17</maven.compiler.source>\n    17→    <maven.compiler.target>17</maven.compiler.target>\n    18→    <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>\n    19→  </properties>\n    20→  <name>roster-ear</name>\n    21→\n    22→  <dependencies>\n    23→    <!-- Pull in the modules we want packaged into the EAR -->\n    24→    <dependency>\n    25→      <groupId>jakarta.tutorial</groupId>\n    26→      <artifactId>roster-common</artifactId>\n    27→      <version>${project.version}</version>\n    28→    </dependency>\n    29→    <dependency>\n    30→      <groupId>jakarta.tutorial</groupId>\n    31→      <artifactId>roster-ejb</artifactId>\n    32→      <version>${project.version}</version>\n    33→      <type>ejb</type>\n    34→    </dependency>\n    35→    <dependency>\n    36→      <groupId>jakarta.tutorial</groupId>\n    37→      <artifactId>roster-appclient</artifactId>\n    38→      <version>${project.version}</version>\n    39→    </dependency>\n    40→    <dependency>\n    41→      <groupId>jakarta.tutorial</groupId>\n    42→      <artifactId>roster-web</artifactId>\n    43→      <version>${project.version}</version>\n    44→      <type>war</type>\n    45→    </dependency>\n    46→    <dependency>\n    47→      <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    48→      <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    49→      <version>2.3.232</version>\n    50→    </dependency>\n    51→  </dependencies>\n    52→\n    53→  <build>\n    54→    <plugins>\n    55→      <plugin>\n    56→        <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>\n    57→        <artifactId>maven-ear-plugin</artifactId>\n    58→        <version>3.3.0</version>\n    59→        <configuration>\n    60→          <generateApplicationXml>true</generateApplicationXml>\n    61→          <defaultLibBundleDir>lib</defaultLibBundleDir>\n    62→          <modules>\n    63→            <ejbModule>\n    64→              <groupId>jakarta.tutorial</groupId>\n    65→              <artifactId>roster-ejb</artifactId>\n    66→            </ejbModule>\n    67→            <jarModule>\n    68→              <groupId>jakarta.tutorial</groupId>\n    69→              <artifactId>roster-appclient</artifactId>\n    70→            </jarModule>\n    71→            <webModule>\n    72→              <groupId>jakarta.tutorial</groupId>\n    73→              <artifactId>roster-web</artifactId>\n    74→              <contextRoot>/roster</contextRoot>\n    75→            </webModule>\n    76→          </modules>\n    77→        </configuration>\n    78→      </plugin>\n    79→      <plugin>\n    80→        <groupId>io.openliberty.tools</groupId>\n    81→        <artifactId>liberty-maven-plugin</artifactId>\n    82→        <configuration>\n    83→          <copyDependencies>\n    84→            <dependencyGroup>\n    85→              <location>${project.build.directory}/liberty/wlp/usr/shared/resources</location>\n    86→              <dependency>\n    87→                <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    88→                <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    89→              </dependency>\n    90→            </dependencyGroup>\n    91→          </copyDependencies>\n    92→        </configuration>\n    93→      </plugin>\n    94→    </plugins>\n    95→  </build>\n    96→</project>\n    97→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"93c908b5-e358-4af1-b262-3899ca8a7105","uuid":"e97f49da-1bfd-49f8-b1e6-fc4c0b2724bc"}
