{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01XifGZKudifHttkTeRctwMd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The .dockerignore is fine. But wait - it excludes `.mvn/` and `mvnw`. Since we're using Maven inside Docker, that's fine since the Docker image already has maven. But I need to make sure the old submodule pom.xml files don't interfere. Let me remove the old module directories or at least ensure Maven doesn't pick them up. Since the parent pom no longer references them (no `<modules>` section), Maven will just build the root pom.\n\nActually, the old module directories still exist on disk. When Docker copies everything, the old module `pom.xml` files will be present but won't be referenced. Let me verify this won't cause issues by checking if Maven somehow picks them up. It shouldn't since the root `pom.xml` no longer has a `<modules>` section. But to be safe, let me just build and see what happens.\n\nLet me now build the Docker image:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":544,"cache_read_input_tokens":81926,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":544,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":650},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"93c908b5-e358-4af1-b262-3899ca8a7105","uuid":"95697ea3-2b20-49ad-8dd7-15d58b894bb4"}
